rces/1142750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142750/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-02","Affordable Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to page 19, I - Housing & Planning (ALB)(Net) of Capital DEL - Communities of his Department's Main Estimates 2019-20 Memorandum, if he will publish details of budgeted expenditure under S01- Building Affordable Homes.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","284327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142751","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-09-05","<p>The Government is committed to maintaining and enhancing workers’ rights as we leave the EU. We will not be bound by EU law but will be able to raise employment standards where it is right for the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) are already working on measures designed to increase take-up of family-related leave and flexible working arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to consulting on high-level options for how we can better balance the gender division of the parental leave and pay system, the department is considering the question of dedicated employment rights for carers alongside existing employment rights (such as the right to request flexible working and the right to time off for family and dependents).</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-09-05T14:18:25.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142751/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142751/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-02","Carers and Parents: Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to implement the European Council directive on work-life balance for parents and carers.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","284329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142752","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-05","<p>The UK State Pension is payable worldwide. It is up-rated for overseas residents where there is a legal requirement to do so and it is up-rated abroad at the same rate as in the UK. <strong> </strong></p><p />","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-09-05T15:31:04.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142752/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142752/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-02","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will take steps to ensure that state pensions for UK citizens living overseas increase at the same rate as pensions for pensioners who remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","284333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142753","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>Eligibility for income-related (means-tested) benefits, such as Universal Credit, depends on a person’s immigration status in the UK.</p><p>EEA nationals who are habitually resident in the UK and have been granted settled status are eligible to access income-related benefits.</p><p>Mechanisms are in place between DWP and the Home Office to verify settled status through the Habitual Residence Test Process.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-09-09T11:00:05.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142753/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142753/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-02","Social Security Benefits: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proof of settled status is required for an EEA national who has been granted settled status and is applying for benefits.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","284336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142754","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-10-01","<p>All EU Member States are bound by Article 1 of Protocol 1 to the European Convention on Human Rights, which obliges them to respect property rights. This includes those who own property, own shares in a property and those who own a property and let it to tenants. UK national’s right to sell their existing property in the EU will remain unchanged and the property tax they pay on their properties will not be affected by the UK leaving the EU.</p><p>Some Member States have laws which govern property and land purchasing that differentiate between their own citizens, EU citizens and Third Country Nationals when purchasing property. Individuals considering purchasing a property in an EU Member State should check with local authorities to confirm how these laws apply to them.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2019-10-01T13:59:12.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142754/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142754/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-09-02","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he is taking to ensure that British citizens with properties in EU member states maintain their rights in the event of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","284339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142755","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government remains committed to publishing best practice guidance on the provision of high quality disability awareness training for bus and coach drivers, to support operators to ensure that every driver has the knowledge and skills to assist disabled passengers.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish the guidance later in the year and will work with the bus and coach industry to encourage its adoption.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-09-09T12:13:28.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142755/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-02","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish the best practice guidance on disability awareness training for bus drivers.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","284341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142756","Department for International Development","false","2019-09-09","<p>The British Government is engaging actively with the Government of Zambia on the drought affecting large parts of Zambia to ensure assistance is provided to the many Zambians facing food insecurity.</p><p>On 29<sup>th</sup> August, the Department for International Development’s (DFID) visiting Director for West and Southern Africa met with the Zambian Minister of Finance and raised the allocation of resources for the drought response. The Head of Office for DFID Zambia and the British High Commissioner also met with the Vice President last month and encouraged Zambia to request international emergency assistance to scale up the response. DFID is in close contact with Zambia’s Disaster Management Response Unit, the United Nations, and international Non-Governmental Organisations on the ground. The UK is planning to provide support to respond through Emergency Cash Transfers and treatment of acute malnutrition in the worst affected areas.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson",,"2019-09-09T15:47:43.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142756/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142756/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-02","Zambia: Droughts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions he has had with his Zambian counterpart on declaring a national emergency in relation to the drought and famine in western and southern Zambia.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","284344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142761","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-10-08","<p>Government strongly encourages all organisations with responsibility for sporting and cultural events, to find sustainable and environmentally-friendly ways of operating.</p><p> </p><p>The EventIMPACTS website, supported by DCMS, provides advice and support for event organisers to help them implement ISO 20121- which is the international standard on sustainable events.</p><p> </p><p>Arts Council England (ACE) support a number of organisations and projects which focus on the environment and sustainability.</p><p> </p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2019-10-08T14:19:06.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142761/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142761/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142761/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-02","Sports: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the role of major sporting and cultural events in the elimination of single use plastics.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","284358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142762","Home Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>Money laundering investigations are a matter for law enforcement agencies, who are operationally independent.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2019-09-09T16:11:29.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142762/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142762/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-02","Football: Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the 92 football league teams have been the subject of money laundering investigations in the last five years; and how many of those investigations are ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","284359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142763","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Feed-In Tariffs scheme was introduced to support the widespread adoption of proven small-scale low-carbon electricity generating technologies. The scheme was intended to give the wider public a stake in the transition to a low-carbon economy and in turn foster behavioural change that would support the development of local supply chains and reductions in energy costs. To date the scheme has supported over 830,000 installations, or 6 GW of capacity.</p><p> </p><p>The Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) is the world’s first long-term financial support programme for renewable heat. The RHI pays participants of the scheme that generate and use renewable heat, or that provide green gas to the gas grid. Under the RHI, the Government has supported over 71,500 homes and over 19,500 businesses, schools, farms and other organisations to install new low carbon heating systems, and these numbers continue to grow (in August 2019 there were over 1,100 domestic applications to participate in the scheme). We estimate that by 2021 the RHI will have supported 21.4 terawatt hours of renewable heat generation. This is equivalent to the annual gas consumption of over 1.6 million households.</p><p> </p><p>In January 2020 the government is introducing a new Smart Export Guarantee, which will ensure that homes and businesses who export their surplus low carbon electricity to the grid can receive payment from their energy suppliers.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-09-09T07:55:02.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142763/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142763/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-02","Renewable Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment she has made of the effect of Government policies on domestic renewable energy installations on their increased potential use in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","284361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142764","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-09-09T16:22:56.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142764/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142764/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-09-02","LEADER Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much and what proportion of the final LEADER allocations have been made to former coalfield constituencies.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","284363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142765","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The guideline on Parkinson’s disease published by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) in July 2017 includes recommendations on managing depression in Parkinson’s in line with its own best practice guidance on depression in people with chronic health problems.</p><p>In addition, NHS England commissions the specialised neurological care that people with Parkinson’s disease may need, and it has set out that such specialised care should include access to psychologists to manage symptoms like anxiety and depression.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-09-09T18:07:43.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142765/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142765/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-02","Parkinson's Disease: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the all-party Parliamentary group on Parkinsons' report entitled, Mental health matters too.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","284365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142767","Cabinet Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Prorogation.</p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-09-09T16:04:38.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142767/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142767/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-02","Electronic Government: Personal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect on fair competition of the five Gov.UK Verify providers being able to re-use Gov.Verify profiles for a period before other market participants are given access to that service.","false","Biography information for Vicky Ford","Chelmsford","Vicky Ford","284369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142768","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-09-05","<p>We believe that meaningful political dialogue, taken forward by Hong Kong under its high degree of autonomy, is the best way to resolve the current impasse. It is important that the basic freedoms enshrined in the Sino-British Joint Declaration are maintained.</p><p>The Sino-British Joint Declaration is a legally binding treaty, registered with the UN, that remains in force. The UK, as a co-signatory, has an obligation to monitor its implementation closely, and we are committed to doing so.</p><p>The Prime Minister discussed developments in Hong Kong with other leaders at the recent G7 Summit. In his discussion with Chinese State Councillor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi on 31 July, the Foreign Secretary raised Hong Kong, including the importance of upholding the ‘One Country, Two Systems’ framework, which is set out in the Joint Declaration.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-09-05T13:49:06.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142768/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142768/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-02","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to uphold the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration; and whether he will support sanctions against persons and institutions that are involved in undermining freedom in Hong Kong.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","284371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142769","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Animal Welfare (Licensing of Activities Involving Animals) (England) (Amendment) Regulations 2019, known as ‘Lucy’s Law’, bans the commercial third party sales of puppies and kittens and will come into force in April 2020. We intend to launch a campaign focused on helping the public understand how to responsibly source a puppy or kitten in early 2020, in the run up to the ban coming into force. The campaign is currently under development.</p>","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith",,"2019-09-09T11:35:36.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142769/answer","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142769/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-09-02","Pets: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made on delivering a public information campaign alongside the introduction of the ban on commercial third-party sales of puppies and kittens in April 2020.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","284374"
