e of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what criteria he will use in deciding whether to use his powers of intervention where a local authority has failed to make sufficient progress in improving its provision for children with special educational needs and disabilities.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","284179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142792","Department for Education","false","2019-09-06","<p>If a local area has failed to make sufficient progress following a special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) revisit by Ofsted and the Care Quality Commission, local area leaders must, as a minimum, submit an updated action plan to the Department for Education, NHS England and the Department for Health and Social Care. The action plan must be co-produced with partners and state how the local area will report on progress and impact, as well as how partners, including families, will be kept fully aware and informed of progress. The action plan will be published and a formal progress review meeting will take place within six months of the revisit report being published. The key partners involved, including the Parent Carer Forum, will be invited to attend this meeting.</p><p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, makes a case-by-case assessment regarding which actions to take following a local area SEND inspection. The outcomes of inspection reports – and particularly where local areas have not made sufficient progress following their revisit by Ofsted and the Care Quality Commission - are key criteria in the Secretary of State’s consideration of the use of intervention powers.</p><p>The Secretary of State has asked Ofsted and the Care Quality Commission to design a programme of further local area SEND inspections to follow the current 5-year round. Discussions around the design and delivery of a possible second cycle are underway but no final decisions have yet been made.</p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch","284179 ; 284440","2019-09-06T17:27:36.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142792/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142792/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-02","Special Educational Needs: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether local area inspections of provision by Ofsted and the Care Quality Commission for children with special educational needs and disabilities will continue beyond 2021.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","284429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142793","Department for Education","false","2019-09-06","<p>The department collects data, via the school census, on pupils identified with a special educational need. This will include some pupils who have a disability, but the department does not collect data on pupils who have a disability but have not been identified with a special educational need.</p><p> </p><p>The department collects and publishes a range of data on outcomes achieved by children, and the published data is generally broken down by a range of characteristics, including pupils identified with special educational needs. A summary of the data published by special educational needs is available in the following publication:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sen-analysis-and-summary-of-data-sources" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sen-analysis-and-summary-of-data-sources</a>.</p><p> </p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch",,"2019-09-06T16:54:41.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142793/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142793/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-02","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what data his Department collects on outcomes achieved by disabled children, including those who have not been formally identified as having a special educational need.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","284443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142794","Treasury","false","2019-09-09","Tax-Free Childcare (TFC) was rolled out throughout 2017 and 2018 to replace childcare vouchers. TFC is better targeted than childcare vouchers, as it broadens access to childcare to all families who meet the eligibility criteria, whether they are an employee or self-employed and regardless of who their employer is. It is also fairer, because support is paid per child rather than per parent, so lone parent households get the same support as those with more than one parent.<p> </p><p>The Government has no plans to re-open the childcare vouchers scheme in the future.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2019-09-09T09:34:36.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142794/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142794/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-09-02","Child Care Vouchers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment has been made of the effect of the closure of Childcare Vouchers to new entrants on working families; and if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of re-opening that scheme.","false","Biography information for Emma Little Pengelly","Belfast South","Emma Little Pengelly","284435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142795","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-09-05","<p>​No minutes relating to meetings between Cambridge Analytica and the then Foreign Secretary, the then Minister for Europe and the Americas, Special Advisors or Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office officials in December 2016 are held by this department.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-09-05T16:07:19.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142795/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142795/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-02","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Cambridge Analytica","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will publish the minutes of meetings between Cambridge Analytica and (a) his predecessor, the Rt Hon. Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip, (b) his Ministers, (c) his special advisers and (d) his officials in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","284184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142796","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>I responded to the hon. Member today.</p>","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Anne-Marie Trevelyan",,"2019-09-09T16:13:04.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142796/answer","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142796/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-02","Ministry of Defence: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to provide substantive answers to Questions 240575 and 240576, tabled by the hon. Member for Edinburgh North and Leith on 3 April 2019.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","284446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142797","Cabinet Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>While the current annual canvass is effective overall in meeting its objectives, it is widely<br>recognised to be outdated, cumbersome and expensive.</p><p>Following consultation with stakeholders, the Government intends to use its powers under section 7 of the Electoral<br>Registration and Administration Act 2013 to amend the legislation governing the annual<br>canvass to make it more streamlined and less prescriptive for Electoral Registration<br>Officers. The draft Representation of the People (Annual Canvass) (Amendment)<br>Regulations 2019 will be laid before Parliament as soon as parliamentary time allows.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-09-09T10:24:24.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142797/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142797/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-02","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to publish the draft Representation of the People (Annual Canvass) (Amendment) Regulations 2019.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","284449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142798","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Department for Transport provides total funding of £70.6m per year which is dedicated to research, development and innovation in the rail industry, as well as additional investment in targeted major modernisation projects such as smart ticketing and digital signalling. Funding for general research and innovation includes projects to support the development of hydrogen-powered trains, with projects researching how they will be approved for entering service, as well as enabling the first mainline testing of a hydrogen train.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS) funds, with industry, a network of university-based centres of excellence for rail research and innovation, as well as committing £11m to a dedicated centre at the University of Leeds. BEIS also offers Industrial Strategy challenge funds for which the rail industry can bid; and has recently announced £40m to explore how the use of hydrogen can be rolled out across the UK, and £100m to enable greater supply of low carbon hydrogen for use across the economy. These funding opportunities will be important to enable hydrogen-powered trains to run on the network in the future.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-09-09T13:22:04.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142798/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142798/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-02","Railways: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to encourage the growth of new rail technologies, including hydrogen-powered trains.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","284451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142799","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>The DfT is committed to promoting innovation through its rail franchise programme and is trialling a three-year pilot fund within the TransPennine Express (TPE) and the Arriva Rail North (Northern) franchises. This is aimed at supporting the development of innovations, focussing on decarbonisation, passenger improvements and capacity and must benefit wider railway and society.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-09-09T12:25:29.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142799/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142799/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-02","Railways: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to promote innovation in the North West rail cluster.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","284188"
