"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142869","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-05","<p>The Government recognises the importance of providing certainty and clarity on the UK Shared Prosperity Fund. There are many detailed design questions to come, on which we welcome input from across the UK.</p><p>It is only right that we take final decisions about the design of the UK Shared Prosperity Fund after a cross-government Spending Review.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-09-05T12:01:22.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142869/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142869/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-02","UK Shared Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the UK Shared Prosperity Fund will provide the same level of funding as that currently provided by EU Structural Funds when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","284270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142870","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government has been clear that should the UK leave the EU without a deal, we would support businesses through whatever appropriate action is necessary.</p><p> </p><p>Programmes operated by the Government owned British Business Bank are currently supporting more than £6.6 billion of finance to over 89,000 SMEs.</p><p> </p><p>In particular, the Enterprise Finance Guarantee (EFG) facilitates business finance to smaller businesses that are viable but unable to obtain finance from their lender due to having insufficient security to meet the lender’s normal requirements.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-09-09T08:45:11.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142870/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142870/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-02","Manufacturing Industries: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether her Department plans to provide cash flow support to manufacturers in the event of the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","284375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142871","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-06","<p>Please accept my apologies for the delay in replying to this question. I can confirm that a response has now been issued.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-09-06T13:41:55.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142871/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142871/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when she plans to respond to Question 270706 on social security benefits, tabled by the hon. Member for Birkenhead on 27 June 2019.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","284380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142872","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>Of the 21,700 claims affected by the policy to provide support for a maximum of two children on Universal Credit in April 2019; 11,500 (53%) received either a new claim or benefit transfer advance, 5,000 (23%) received a budgeting advance. Of those with new claim or benefit transfer advance 3,100 (14%) also received a budgeting advance.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-09-09T16:03:20.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142872/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142872/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants, who are affected by the policy to provide support for a maximum of two children, have received (a) a payment advance on their claim, (b) a budgeting advance on their claim and (c) both.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","284273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142873","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-09-05","<p>We believe that meaningful political dialogue, taken forward by Hong Kong under its high degree of autonomy, is the best way to resolve the current impasse. It is important that the basic freedoms enshrined in the Sino-British Joint Declaration are maintained.</p><p>The Sino-British Joint Declaration is a legally binding treaty, registered with the UN, that remains in force. The UK, as a co-signatory, has an obligation to monitor its implementation closely, and we are committed to doing so.</p><p>The Prime Minister discussed developments in Hong Kong with other leaders at the recent G7 Summit. In his discussion with Chinese State Councillor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi on 31 July, the Foreign Secretary raised Hong Kong, including the importance of upholding the ‘One Country, Two Systems’ framework, which is set out in the Joint Declaration.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-09-05T13:42:05.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142873/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142873/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-02","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Chinese authorities on the status of the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration on Hong Kong; and obligations the Government has to monitor the implementation of the principles established in that Declaration.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","284277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142874","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government is committed to developing and implementing the Code of Practice as soon as possible. We are currently considering the options for the delivery of the Code and the design of the levy on industry, as well as the format for stakeholder engagement. We will make an announcement in due course. We are also committed to carrying out a public consultation on the draft Code of Practice, allowing all interested parties to directly respond to the proposals.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","284789","2019-09-09T15:27:53.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142874/answer","Biography information for Luke Hall","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142874/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-02","Parking: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Parking (Code of Practice) Act 2019, what the next steps are in developing the code of practice.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","284387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142875","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-09","<p>Consistent with the requirement of the Act that the Code of Practice be developed in consultation with stakeholders, we are currently considering the format for stakeholder engagement and will make an announcement in due course. We are also committed to carrying out a public consultation on the draft Code of Practice as part of the development process, allowing all interested parties to directly respond to the proposals.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","285286","2019-09-09T15:28:33.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142875/answer","Biography information for Luke Hall","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142875/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-02","Codes of Practice: Parking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2019 to Question 266813 on Parking (Code of Practice) Act 2019, what options are being considered for the format of the stakeholder engagement during the development of the code of practice.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","284279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142876","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-09-09","<p>We are committed to increasing the supply of social housing to further support struggling families and those at risk of homelessness. We have invested over £9 billion into our Affordable Homes Programme to deliver approximately 250,000 affordable homes by 2022, including at least 12,500 for social rent in areas of acute affordability pressure.</p><p>We have increased the size of the Affordable Homes Programme, re-introduced social rent, removed the Housing Revenue Account (HRA) borrowing cap for local authorities, and have set out a long-term rent deal for councils and housing associations in England from 2020. Housing associations and local authorities now need to accelerate delivery and build more affordable homes.</p><p>Since 2010, we have delivered over 430,000 new affordable homes, including over 308,000 affordable homes for rent.</p><p>On 18 September we announced an additional £2 billion of long-term funding certainty for housing associations. This extra funding will deliver more affordable homes and stimulate the sector’s wider building ambitions, through strategic partnerships.</p><p>We do not publish yearly targets but, deliver flexibly throughout the years of the programme to achieve our overall target and hold Homes England and the Greater London Authority (GLA) to account for delivery.</p><p>We will continue to provide opportunities for more people to afford home ownership and seek to build on the progress that has been made on building new social homes.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey",,"2019-09-09T15:22:51.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142876/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142876/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-02","Social Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will commit to building 100,000 homes for social rent per year.","false","Biography information for Faisal Rashid","Warrington South","Faisal Rashid","284283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142877","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-09-09","<p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, which take into account the circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors. We are clear that sentencing must match the severity of a crime.</p><p> </p><p>Prison numbers can fluctuate, which is why we have a robust set of plans in place to ensure we will always have enough places for offenders sent to custody by the courts. The Prime Minister recently announced his ambition to transform the prison estate with an additional investment of £2.5 billion which will deliver 10,000 additional prison places.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-09-09T11:39:17.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142877/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142877/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-02","Prison Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to reduce the prison population.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","284391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142878","Department for Education","false","2019-09-09","<p>We want parents to have access to a range of affordable childcare, giving them increased flexibility in their working hours and helping children thrive in the crucial early years. That is why the department is investing £3.5 billion in our early education offers this year alone. The cost of 30 hours free childcare is set in table 1, attached. The total for 2017-18 is due to rounding.</p><p>The number of children that have benefitted from 30 hours free childcare in each year is set out in table 2, attached.</p><p>In total, around 600,000 children aged 3 and 4 years old benefitted from a 30 hours place throughout the first 2 years of delivery.</p><p>We do not hold data on estimates of the number of parents that have benefitted from the 30 hours entitlement in England.</p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch","284299 ; 284402 ; 285420 ; 285422","2019-09-09T14:23:32.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142878/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142878/answer","284299_284395_284402_285420_285422_30_hours_childcare.xls","284299_284395_284402_285420_285422_table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142878/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-02","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse was of the 30 hour free childcare scheme in England in the 2018-19 financial year.","false","Biography information for Emma Little Pengelly","Belfast South","Emma Little Pengelly","284395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142879","Department for Education","false","2019-09-06","<p>The 30 hours childcare schemes are a devolved matter and the Department for Education has a remit for the 30 hours entitlement for England. Questions about schemes in Scotland and Wales should be referred to the devolved administrations.</p>","Saffron Walden","Mrs Kemi Badenoch","284292 ; 284294 ; 284406 ; 285418 ; 285419","2019-09-06T17:40:13.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142879/answer","Biography information for Mrs Kemi Badenoch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142879/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-02","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse was of the 30 hour free childcare scheme in Wales in the 2018-19 financial year.","false","Biography information for Emma Little Pengelly","Belfast South","Emma Little Pengelly","284288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142880","Department for Transport","false","2019-09-09","<p>A decision on the transfer of these services will be dependent on a successful business case being made and will also have to be aligned with the Department’s plan for the future of TSGN. This plan will have to take into account the recommendations of the Williams Rail Review, which reports in the autumn.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-09-09T12:21:09.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142880/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1142880/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-02","Great Northern Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to support the transfer of the Great Northern Rail Line from Govia Thameslink to Transport for London.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","284399"
